\mt1 1 Timothy
\is1 Introduction
\ip Timothy was a Christian from Asia. His mother was a Jew but his father was a Greek. When Paul saw Timothy's genuine faith, he accepted him as one of his companions and helpers at preaching and telling of good message (Acts 16:1-3) and they had ended up in Ephesus together, where Paul left Timothy behind in order to look after the new believers there. After Timothy had been in Ephesus for some time, Paul sent this letter to him. Timothy's age was likely around thirty at that time.
\ip There are three purposes in this letter of Paul to Timothy:
\ip 1.) The first purpose of Paul, warned sikandin concerning the not true/correct teaching there to group of believers. This teaching, nenekegsewug e of me suman-suman of Jews and of non-Jews. Su sumale kandan bad this the world mig-ugpaan ta. Ne and kun just egkaluwas the person ke due wisdom/knowledge din and not egpangeen of duma class of food and not also eg-asawa. Taught si Paul not true/correct sika.
\ip 2.) Taught again this letter concerning the carrying of group of believers and of worshipping. Written here the correct behaviour of one teacher of believers, of helper of believers and of duma believers widows and slaves.
\ip 3.) Finally he advised Timothy how to become good servant of Jesus the messiah, and concerning his responsibility to believers.
\iot Main components of Paul's letter
\io1 Introduction \ior 1:1-2\ior*
\io1 The teaching concerning the group of believers and of teachers \ior 1:3–3:16\ior*
\io1 The teaching to Timothy concerning his work \ior 4:1–6:21\ior*
